    "en": {
      "title": "Monkeypox triples in Europe and Africa",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "Monkeypox cases have tripled in the past two weeks in the European region, the European head of the World Health Organization (WHO) warned on Friday, urging countries to do more to ensure the previously rare disease does not take root on the continent.",
        "Dr. Hans Kluge, the head of WHO Europe, said in a statement that despite the UN health agency's decision last week, more efforts were needed.",
        "\"Urgent and coordinated action is essential if we are to turn a corner in this game to reverse the spread of this disease,\" Kluge said.",
        "African health authorities said they were treating the spread of monkeypox as an emergency and were urging rich countries to share limited vaccine supplies to avoid the equity problems seen during the Covid-19 pandemic.",
        "According to the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, more than 5,000 cases of monkeypox have been reported today in 51 countries around the world that do not normally report the disease. Kluge said the number of infections in Europe is about 90% of the global total, and 31 countries in the WHO European Region have identified cases.",
        "It is revealed that the patients are equally divided between men and women."
      ],
